Machine learning Project : Personal Loan Campaign¶

Context¶

All Life Bank, a US-based institution, has a growing customer base primarily made up of depositors. Only a small segment also takes loans. The bank seeks to expand this borrower base to boost loan-related revenue by converting more depositors into personal loan customers, while retaining their deposits. A previous campaign targeting depositors saw a successful 9% conversion rate, motivating the marketing team to pursue more focused efforts. As a data scientist, your role is to develop a model to help identify depositors most likely to take personal loans.

Objective¶

To predict whether liability customer will buy personal loans, to understand which customer attributes are most significant in driving purchases and to identify which segment of customers to target more.

questions to be answered?¶

  • Which customer attributes are most significant in driving purchases?
  • Which segment of customers should be targeted more?
  • What is the predicted likelihood of a liability customer buying a personal loan?

Dataset¶

  • ID: Customer ID
  • Age : Customers age in completed years
  • Experience: # Years of professional experience
  • Income: Annual income of customer (in thousand dollars)
  • Zip Code: Home Address ZIP code
  • Family: The family size of the customer
  • CCAvg: Average spending on credit cards per month (in thousand dollars)
  • Education: Education level. 1:Undergrad; 2:Graduate; 3:Advanced/Professional
  • Mortgage: Value of house Mortgage if any.(in thousand dollars)
  • Personal_Loan: did this customer accept the personal loan offered in the last campaign?
  • Securities_Account: Does the customer have securities account with the bank?
  • CD_Account: Does the customer have a certificate of deposit(CD) with the bank?
  • Online:Do customers use Internet banking facilities?
  • CreditCard:Does the customer use credit card issued by any other bank(excluding All Life Bank)?

  • Age: The distributions customers who took a loan and those who did not are relatively similar across age groups. There isn't a very strong visual separation based on age alone, suggesting age might not be the primary driver for personal loan uptake compared to other factors.
  • Experience: Similar to Age, the experience distribution for loan takers and non-loan takers largely overlaps. Professional experience alone doesn't appear to be a strong differentiator for personal loan likelihood.
  • Income: This plot shows a significant difference. Customers who took a personal loan tend to have substantially higher incomes compared to those who did not take a loan. The distribution for Personal_Loan=1 is skewed towards higher income brackets. Income appears to be a very important factor.
  • CCAvg (Credit Card Average Spending): Customers with higher average credit card spending per month are more likely to have taken a personal loan. The distribution for Personal_Loan=1 is shifted towards higher CCAvg values, indicating a correlation between higher spending and personal loan acceptance.
  • Mortgage: The distribution of mortgage values is quite similar for both groups (Personal_Loan=0 and Personal_Loan=1), with both having a large peak at zero (no mortgage). While there are customers with mortgages in both groups, having a mortgage doesn't appear to strongly distinguish between loan takers and non-loan takers based on this plot.

In summary, Income and CCAvg seem to be the most visually significant numerical features for predicting whether a customer will take a personal loan, with higher values in these features being associated with a higher likelihood of taking a loan. Age and Experience show less clear separation based on loan status. Mortgage also doesn't appear to be a strong individual predictor from these histograms.

Multivariate Analysis¶

In [61]:
# Correlation heatmap for numerical variables
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
sns.heatmap(Ploan[numerical_columns + ['Personal_Loan']].corr(), annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', fmt=".2f")
plt.title('Correlation Matrix of Numerical Variables')
plt.show()

Here are some observations based on the provided correlation heatmap:

  1. Income and Personal_Loan have the highest positive correlation (0.50). This confirms the univariate analysis observation that higher income is strongly associated with a higher likelihood of taking a personal loan.
  2. CCAvg and Personal_Loan also have a strong positive correlation (0.37). This reinforces the idea that customers who spend more on credit cards monthly are more likely to accept a personal loan offer.
  3. Income and CCAvg are moderately positively correlated (0.65). This suggests that customers with higher incomes tend to have higher average credit card spending, which makes sense intuitively.
  4. Experience and Age are very highly positively correlated (0.99). This is expected as professional experience typically increases with age. This high correlation suggests potential multicollinearity if both are used directly in certain models, though for decision trees it's less of a concern.
  5. Mortgage has a very low positive correlation with Personal_Loan (0.14). This supports the observation from the univariate analysis that the mortgage value doesn't seem to be a significant predictor of taking a personal loan.
  6. Age and Experience have weak or negligible correlations with Personal_Loan (0.00 and -0.01, respectively). This further confirms that these features, while potentially useful in conjunction with others, do not individually show a strong linear relationship with the target variable.
  7. Other correlations among numerical variables are generally weak to moderate (e.g., Income with Age/Experience).

Key Takeaways from the Correlation Heatmap:

  • Income and CCAvg are the strongest numerical predictors of Personal_Loan status based on linear correlation.
  • Age and Experience are highly correlated with each other but have negligible linear correlation with Personal_Loan.
  • Mortgage has no linear correlation with Personal_Loan.

This reinforces the importance of Income and CCAvg in predicting personal loan acceptance and suggests that Age, Experience, and Mortgage may be less crucial as standalone linear predictors, although their interactions or non-linear relationships might still be relevant.

# outlier detection using boxplot

# Selects numerical columns from the DataFrame `data` using `select_dtypes(include=np.number)` and converts the column names to a list.
numeric_columns = data.select_dtypes(include=np.number).columns.tolist()
# Creates a new figure and a set of subplots with a specified figure size.
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 12))
# Loops through the list of numerical column names and their index.
for i, variable in enumerate(numeric_columns): #Iterate through each column
    # Creates a subplot in the current figure. The layout is 4 rows by 4 columns, and the current subplot is at position i + 1.
    plt.subplot(4, 4, i + 1)
    # Generates a box plot for the current numerical variable. `whis=1.5` sets the length of the whiskers.
    plt.boxplot(data[variable], whis=1.5) # plot the boxplot
    # Adjusts subplot parameters for a tight layout.
    plt.tight_layout()
    # Sets the title of the current subplot to the name of the variable.
    plt.title(variable)
# Displays the plots.
plt.show()

Observations

  • There are quite a few outliers in the data.
  • However, we will not treat them as they are proper values

Creating training and test sets.

In [67]:
# encoding the categorical variables

# X will contain all columns except 'Personal_Loan', representing the features.
X = Ploan.drop(["Personal_Loan"], axis=1)
# Y will contain only the 'Personal_Loan' column, representing the target variable.
Y = data["Personal_Loan"]

# Converting categorical features into dummy/indicator variables.
# 'drop_first=True' is used to avoid multicollinearity by dropping the first category.
X = pd.get_dummies(X, drop_first=True)

# Converting the data type of X to float. This is often required for various machine learning algorithms.
X = X.astype(float)

# Splitting data in train and test sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X, Y, test_size=0.30, random_state=1
)

Model Building¶

Model Evaluation Criterion¶

Model can make wrong predictions as:

  1. Predicting a customer will not take a personal Loan but in reality the customer will take a personal Loan. False Negative (Type II error).

  2. Predicting a customer will take a personal loan but in reality the customer will not take a loan. False Positive (Type I error).

Which case is more important?

  • If we predict a customer will not take a personal loan but in reality he will take a personal loan, bank would lose an opportunity of providing loan to a potential customer.
  • If we predict a customer will take a loan but in reality he will not take a loan, bank's marketing and operating costs would be wasted.

How to reduce this loss i.e need to reduce False Negatives?

  • recall should be maximized, the greater the recall higher the chances of minimizing the false negatives.

First, let's create functions to calculate different metrics and confusion matrix so that we don't have to use the same code repeatedly for each model.¶

  • The model_performance_classification_sklearn function will be used to check the model performance of models.
  • The confusion_matrix_sklearn function will be used to plot confusion matrix.
In [69]:
# defining a function to compute different metrics to check performance of a classification model built using sklearn
def model_performance_classification_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {"Accuracy": acc, "Recall": recall, "Precision": precision, "F1": f1,},
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf
In [70]:
def confusion_matrix_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    To plot the confusion_matrix with percentages

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """
    y_pred = model.predict(predictors)
    cm = confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="")
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")

Decision Tree (Pre-pruning)¶

  • Hyperparameter tuning is crucial because it directly affects the performance of a model.
  • Unlike model parameters which are learned during training, hyperparameters need to be set before training.
  • Effective hyperparameter tuning helps in improving the performance and robustness of the model.
  • The below custom loop for hyperparameter tuning iterates over predefined parameter values to identify the best model based on the metric of choice (recall score).
In [80]:
# Define the parameters of the tree to iterate over
max_depth_values = np.arange(2, 7, 2)  # to iterate over the different values of maximum depth
max_leaf_nodes_values = [50, 75, 150, 250]  # to iterate over the different values of maximum leaf nodes
min_samples_split_values = [10, 30, 50, 70]  # to iterate over the different values of minimum samples split

# Initialize variables to store the best model and its performance
best_estimator = None
best_score_diff = float('inf')
best_test_score = 0.0

# Iterate over all combinations of the specified parameter values
for max_depth in max_depth_values:
    for max_leaf_nodes in max_leaf_nodes_values:
        for min_samples_split in min_samples_split_values:

            # Initialize the tree with the current set of parameters
            estimator = DecisionTreeClassifier(
                max_depth=max_depth,
                max_leaf_nodes=max_leaf_nodes,
                min_samples_split=min_samples_split,
                class_weight='balanced',
                random_state=42
            )

            # Fit the model to the training data
            estimator.fit(X_train, y_train)

            # Make predictions on the training and test sets
            y_train_pred = estimator.predict(X_train)
            y_test_pred = estimator.predict(X_test)

            # Calculate recall scores for training and test sets
            train_recall_score = recall_score(y_train, y_train_pred)
            test_recall_score = recall_score(y_test, y_test_pred)

            # Calculate the absolute difference between training and test recall scores
            score_diff = abs(train_recall_score - test_recall_score)

            # Update the best estimator and best score if the current one has a smaller score difference
            if (score_diff < best_score_diff) & (test_recall_score > best_test_score):
                best_score_diff = score_diff
                best_test_score = test_recall_score
                best_estimator = estimator

# creating an instance of the best model
model1 = best_estimator

# Print the best parameters
print("Best parameters found:")
print(f"Max depth: {best_estimator.max_depth}")
print(f"Max leaf nodes: {best_estimator.max_leaf_nodes}")
print(f"Min samples split: {best_estimator.min_samples_split}")
print(f"Best test recall score: {best_test_score}")

Decision Tree (Post pruning)¶

  • Cost complexity pruning provides another option to control the size of a tree.
  • In DecisionTreeClassifier, this pruning technique is parameterized by the cost complexity parameter, ccp_alpha.
  • Greater values of ccp_alpha increase the number of nodes pruned.
  • Here we only show the effect of ccp_alpha on regularizing the trees and how to choose the optimal ccp_alpha value.

Total impurity of leaves vs effective alphas of pruned tree

Minimal cost complexity pruning recursively finds the node with the "weakest link". The weakest link is characterized by an effective alpha, where the nodes with the smallest effective alpha are pruned first. To get an idea of what values of ccp_alpha could be appropriate, scikit-learn provides DecisionTreeClassifier.cost_complexity_pruning_path that returns the effective alphas and the corresponding total leaf impurities at each step of the pruning process. As alpha increases, more of the tree is pruned, which increases the total impurity of its leaves.

In [89]:
# Fit the Decision Tree classifier to the training data with default parameters and a specified random state for reproducibility.
clf = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=1)

# Calculate the pruning path based on cost complexity.
# This function returns the effective alphas and the corresponding total leaf impurities
# at each step of the pruning process.
path = clf.cost_complexity_pruning_path(X_train, y_train)

# Extract the different `ccp_alpha` values from the pruning path.
# These values represent the thresholds for pruning. A higher alpha value results in more pruning.
ccp_alphas, impurities = path.ccp_alphas, path.impurities

Next, we train a decision tree using the effective alphas. The last value in ccp_alphas is the alpha value that prunes the whole tree, leaving the tree, clfs[-1], with one node.

In [92]:
# Train a Decision Tree for each effective alpha value obtained from the pruning path.
# We exclude the last alpha value because it prunes the entire tree to a single node.
clfs = [] # Initialize an empty list to store the trained Decision Tree classifiers
for ccp_alpha in ccp_alphas:
    # Create a Decision Tree Classifier instance with the current ccp_alpha and a fixed random state for reproducibility.
    # class_weight='balanced' can be added here if you want to handle class imbalance during training,
    # but the example code does not include it, so we'll keep it simple for this step.
    clf = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=1, ccp_alpha=ccp_alpha)

    # Train the current Decision Tree classifier on the training data (X_train, y_train).
    clf.fit(X_train, y_train)

    # Append the trained classifier to the list of classifiers.
    clfs.append(clf)
print(
    "Number of nodes in the last tree is: {} with ccp_alpha: {}".format(
        clfs[-1].tree_.node_count, ccp_alphas[-1]
    )
)
# Note: clfs[-1] will be the tree trained with the largest ccp_alpha value, which results in a single-node tree (the root node).
# This tree effectively prunes the entire tree and is the result of the final pruning step.
# clfs[0] corresponds to the original, unpruned tree (ccp_alpha=0).

Evaluation based on Objective (Maximizing Recall):

The problem statement emphasizes identifying customers most likely to take personal loans, which means minimizing False Negatives. Therefore, Recall is the most critical metric.

Pre-Pruning: Achieves perfect Recall (1.0) on both training and test sets. This means it identifies all customers who took a personal loan in the test set. However, its Precision is very low (0.310), meaning for every 10 customers it predicts will take a loan, only about 3 actually do. This would lead to significant wasted resources in targeting.

Post-Pruning: Achieves a high Recall (0.906) on the test set, which means it identifies about 90.6% of the actual loan takers. Its Precision is also high (0.931), meaning when it predicts someone will take a loan, it's correct about 93.1% of the time.

Conclusion:

While the Decision Tree (Pre-Pruning) model achieves the highest Recall (1.0) on the test set, its extremely low Precision makes it impractical. The bank would be targeting a huge number of customers who will not take a loan, leading to significant marketing costs.

The Decision Tree (Post-Pruning) model offers a better balance between Recall and Precision on the test set. It identifies a large proportion of the actual loan takers (high Recall of 0.906) while also being relatively accurate in its positive predictions (high Precision of 0.931). This leads to a higher F1 score (0.918), which is the harmonic mean of Recall and Precision and provides a better overall measure of the model's performance for imbalanced datasets where both false positives and false negatives have costs.

The Decision Tree (sklearn default) model clearly overfits and performs worse than the post-pruned model on the test set.

Therefore, based on the objective of identifying potential loan takers efficiently (considering both finding them and not wasting resources on false positives), the Decision Tree (Post-Pruning) model is the better choice. It offers a strong balance of identifying most loan takers while maintaining a reasonable level of precision in its targeting.

Key Takeaways for the Marketing Team & Advice for the Campaign:¶

Based on the data analysis and the performance of the chosen Post-Pruned Decision Tree model (Recall: ~0.91, Precision: ~0.93 on the test set), here are the key takeaways and advice for the personal loan campaign:

  1. Target the Right Customer Segments: The model identifies customers most likely to accept a personal loan. Do NOT use a blanket approach. Focus your marketing efforts and resources on the customers identified as potential loan takers by the model. This will significantly increase your conversion rate compared to the previous campaign's 9%.

  2. Prioritize Based on Key Attributes: The most influential factors in predicting loan acceptance are:

    • Income: Customers with higher incomes are significantly more likely to take a loan.
    • Education Level: Customers with an 'Advanced/Professional' education are more prone to taking loans.
    • Family Size: Customers with a family size of 4 show a higher propensity for loan uptake.
    • CCAvg (Average Credit Card Spending): Customers with higher average monthly credit card spending are also more likely candidates.
    • CD Account: Customers who already have a CD account with the bank are more likely to accept a personal loan offer.

  3. Tailor Your Messaging:

    • Highlight the benefits of a personal loan in relation to high income and spending habits. Position the loan as a way to manage finances better, invest, or fulfill aspirations for those with higher incomes and spending.
    • For customers with 'Advanced/Professional' education, tailor the message to appeal to their financial sophistication and potential need for capital for professional or personal growth.
    • Consider messaging that resonates with larger families (size 4), potentially focusing on needs like home improvements, education expenses, or consolidating debts.
    • Leverage the fact that customers with a CD Account are likely to be financially engaged. Position the personal loan as another valuable financial product from the bank they already trust.

  4. Utilize the Model for High-Probability Leads: The post-pruned decision tree model achieved a good balance of identifying about 90.6% of actual loan takers (high Recall) while being correct in its positive predictions about 93.1% of the time (high Precision). This means the list of customers the model predicts will take a loan is highly reliable. Focus initial and most intensive marketing efforts on this list.

  5. Optimize Resource Allocation: By targeting only the high-probability leads identified by the model, the bank can drastically reduce wasted marketing spend on customers who are unlikely to convert. This allows for more effective use of budget on personalized outreach, higher-quality marketing materials, or even special offers for the targeted segment.

  6. Consider Channel Strategy: Analyze which channels (email, mail, in-branch, online ads) are most effective for these specific customer segments based on their demographics (age, online usage) and existing relationships (CD account holders, credit card users).

  7. Continuous Monitoring and Refinement: This model is a starting point. Continuously track the conversion rate of the targeted customers. Collect feedback from the marketing team and sales channels. Use the results of this campaign to refine the model and targeting strategy for future campaigns.

In summary, the advice is to shift from a broad marketing campaign to a highly targeted, data-driven approach. Use the insights from the model, particularly the importance of Income, Education (Adv/Prof), Family size 4, CCAvg, and CD Account, to identify the most promising customers and tailor the marketing message to resonate with their specific financial profiles and needs. The post-pruned decision tree model provides the predicted customer list to achieve this efficient targeting.

Conclusion and Recommendations¶

Conclusions:

  1. Significant Predictors Identified: The analysis clearly highlighted several key factors strongly associated with a customer's likelihood of taking a personal loan:

    • Income and CCAvg (Average Credit Card Spending): These were the most influential numerical features, with higher values in both indicating a much higher propensity for loan uptake.
    • Education Level: Customers with an 'Advanced/Professional' education were significantly more likely to take a loan.
    • CD Account: Having a Certificate of Deposit (CD) account was also a strong indicator of loan acceptance.
    • Family Size 4: Customers with a family size of 4 showed a higher likelihood of taking a personal loan.
    • Features like Age, Experience (which is highly correlated with Age), Mortgage, Securities Account, Online banking usage, and Credit Card usage (from other banks) were found to be less influential as standalone predictors compared to Income, CCAvg, Education, and CD Account.

  2. Class Imbalance: The dataset exhibits significant class imbalance, with a large majority of customers not taking a personal loan. This was addressed by focusing on metrics beyond simple accuracy, particularly Recall for the minority class (loan takers).

  3. Model Performance:

    • The default Decision Tree model severely overfit the training data, achieving perfect scores but generalizing poorly to the test set.
    • Both pre-pruning and post-pruning techniques successfully addressed the overfitting issue.
    • The Decision Tree (Post-Pruning) model offers a better balance between Recall and Precision on the test set. It identifies a large proportion of the actual loan takers (high Recall of 0.906) while also being relatively accurate in its positive predictions (high Precision of 0.931). This leads to a higher F1 score (0.918), which is the harmonic mean of Recall and Precision and provides a better overall measure of the model's performance for imbalanced datasets where both false positives and false negatives have costs

Recommendations:

  1. Targeted Marketing Campaigns: The bank should focus its personal loan marketing efforts on customer segments identified as most likely to accept:

    • Customers with high income and high average credit card spending.
    • Customers with 'Advanced/Professional' education.
    • Customers who currently hold a CD Account with the bank.
    • Customers with a family size of 4.

  2. Leverage Customer Data: Utilize existing customer data on income, CCAvg, education level, family size, and CD account status to identify and prioritize high-potential leads for personal loan offers.

  3. Refine Offers: Tailor personal loan offers based on customer segments. For instance, offers to high-income, high-spending customers might focus on larger loan amounts or premium features, while offers to customers with CD accounts could highlight synergies or bundled benefits.

  4. Explore Feature Interactions: While Income and CCAvg are strong individual predictors, the multivariate analysis (e.g., Income vs. Education colored by loan status) suggests that interactions between features are also important. Future analysis or models could explicitly capture these interactions for potentially better predictions.

  5. Monitor and Iterate: Implement the model's recommendations for targeted campaigns and continuously monitor the conversion rates. Use feedback from campaigns to refine the model and targeting strategy over time.

By implementing these recommendations, All Life Bank can significantly improve the efficiency and success rate of its personal loan campaigns by focusing resources on the customers most likely to convert.
